=\"pun\">));</span> <span class=\"pun\">?&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n            <span class=\"tag\">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class=\"com\">&lt;!-- /#post-&lt;?php get_the_ID(); ?&gt; --&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n        <span class=\"pun\">&lt;?</span><span class=\"pln\">php endwhile</span><span class=\"pun\">;</span> <span class=\"pun\">?&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n		<span class=\"tag\">&lt;div</span> <span class=\"atn\">class</span><span class=\"pun\">=</span><span class=\"atv\">\"navigation\"</span><span class=\"tag\">&gt;</span>\r\n			<span class=\"tag\">&lt;span</span> <span class=\"atn\">class</span><span class=\"pun\">=</span><span class=\"atv\">\"newer\"</span><span class=\"tag\">&gt;</span><span class=\"pun\">&lt;?</span><span class=\"pln\">php previous_posts_link</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"pln\">__</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"str\">\'« Newer\'</span><span class=\"pun\">,</span><span class=\"str\">\'example\'</span><span class=\"pun\">))</span> <span class=\"pun\">?&gt;</span><span class=\"tag\">&lt;/span&gt;</span> <span class=\"tag\">&lt;span</span> <span class=\"atn\">class</span><span class=\"pun\">=</span><span class=\"atv\">\"older\"</span><span class=\"tag\">&gt;</span><span class=\"pun\">&lt;?</span><span class=\"pln\">php next_posts_link</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"pln\">__</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"str\">\'Older »\'</span><span class=\"pun\">,</span><span class=\"str\">\'example\'</span><span class=\"pun\">))</span> <span class=\"pun\">?&gt;</span><span class=\"tag\">&lt;/span&gt;</span>\r\n		<span class=\"tag\">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class=\"com\">&lt;!-- /.navigation --&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n	<span class=\"pun\">&lt;?</span><span class=\"pln\">php </span><span class=\"kwd\">else</span><span class=\"pun\">:</span> <span class=\"pun\">?&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n		<span class=\"tag\">&lt;div</span> <span class=\"atn\">id</span><span class=\"pun\">=</span><span class=\"atv\">\"post-404\"</span> <span class=\"atn\">class</span><span class=\"pun\">=</span><span class=\"atv\">\"noposts\"</span><span class=\"tag\">&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n		    <span class=\"tag\">&lt;p&gt;</span><span class=\"pun\">&lt;?</span><span class=\"pln\">php _e</span><span class=\"pun\">(</span><span class=\"str\">\'None found.\'</span><span class=\"pun\">,</span><span class=\"str\">\'example\'</span><span class=\"pun\">);</span> <span class=\"pun\">?&gt;</span><span class=\"tag\">&lt;/p&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n	    <span class=\"tag\">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class=\"com\">&lt;!-- /#post-404 --&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n	<span class=\"pun\">&lt;?</span><span class=\"pln\">php endif</span><span class=\"pun\">;</span><span class=\"pln\"> wp_reset_query</span><span class=\"pun\">();</span> <span class=\"pun\">?&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n	<span class=\"tag\">&lt;/div&gt;</span><span class=\"com\">&lt;!-- /#content --&gt;</span>\r\n\r\n<span class=\"pun\">&lt;?</span><span class=\"pln\">php get_footer</span><span class=\"pun\">();</span> <span class=\"pun\">?&gt;</span></code></pre>\r\n</div>','Starting Quickly with Wordpress and going from there','','inherit','closed','closed','','495-revision-v1','','','2017-08-05 06:50:36','2017-08-05 06:50:36','',495,'http://www.localhost/fco/495-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(498,1,'2017-08-05 15:37:21','2017-08-05 15:37:21','Not well  documented but I think i have figured it out.... Only stack exchange offered manual answers, and there was a wp plugin. All other solutions are expensive as hell.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nobviously in 2010 it was still an issue\r\n\r\nfound this round about way on the way bottom of the discussion\r\n\r\nhttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/846659/how-can-i-put-a-database-under-git-version-control/28123546#28123546\r\n\r\ncool video though\r\n\r\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c45AevIuYGk\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nin 2012 there was an answer, and one Im considering\r\n<h3 class=\"r\"><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/13608706/using-version-control-git-on-a-mysql-database\">Using version control (Git) on a MySQL database - Stack Overflow</a></h3>\r\nhttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/13608706/using-version-control-git-on-a-mysql-database\r\n\r\nQ:\r\n\r\nI am a WordPress Designer/Developer, who is getting more and more heavily involved with using version control, notably Git, though I do use SVN for some projects. I am currently using Beanstalk for my remote repo.\r\n\r\nAdding all of the WordPress files to my repo is no problem, if I wanted to I know I could .gitignore the wp-config file, but since I\'m the only developer, currently, and these projects are closed source, it really makes little sense.\r\n\r\nWordPress relies heavily on the database, as any CMS does, to keep textual content, and many settings depending on the specific plugin/theme configuration I\'m using. I\'m wondering what the best way of using version control on the database would be, if it\'s even possible. I guess I could do a SQL dump, though my MySQL server is running on Windows (read as: I don\'t know how to do it), and then add the SQL dump to my repository. But when I push something live, that poses huge security threats.\r\n\r\nIs there an accepted practice of doing this?\r\n\r\nA:\r\n\r\nYou can backup your database within a git repository. Of course, if you place the data into git in a binary form, you will lose all of git\'s ability to efficiently store the data using diffs (changes). So the number one best practice is this: store the data in a text serialised format.\r\n\r\nmysqldump is a suitable program to help you do this. It isn\'t perfect though. If anything disturbs the serialisation order of items (eg. as a result of creating new tables, etc.) then artificial breaks will enter into the diff. That will decrease the efficiency of storage. You could write a custom serialiser to serialise changes only -- but then you are doing the hard work that git is already good at. Just use the sql dump.\r\n\r\nThat being said, what you are wanting to do isn\'t what devs normally mean when they talk about putting the database in git. For instance, if you read the link posted by @eggyal (<a href=\"http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/2008/02/get-your-database-under-version-control.html\">link to codinghorror</a>) you will see that what is actually placed in git are the scripts needed to generate the initial database. There may be additional scripts, like those to populate the database data with a clean state, or to populate it with testing data. All such sql scripts are text files, and pretty much the same format as the sql dump you would get from mysqldump. So there\'s no reason you can\'t do it that way with your day-to-day data as well.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nthen theres this wp plugin, which i will also try\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/wp-sync-db/wp-sync-db\r\n\r\nI tried the wp sync. install and making it work took about an hour with everythign said and done. thats the first time i used a github wp plugin though. It wont work for our purposes as I realized that versioning the database will be crucial to working simultaneously in wordpress with someone other than myself.  It wont be crucial if they are just changing the javascript things though. Since this is easy, compressable, and now its installed I might choose this. option.\r\n\r\nI have also been tryign different file types to see if github is able to parse and make them versionable.... may have found the one. I saved the DB as CodeGen and a .cs file came out that looks incredibly promising. Turns out github was not able to detect the content changes. I tried php and .sql file types and it looks okay.  The diffs are the most detailed out of all the text files. Upon further testing i found that after i changed the file and replaced it and then did it agian. the .sql file updated correctly while the .phop file did not. Also it looks as though the .sql file was much more detailed in its diffs. The one redeemign quality about using .php was that the files are much more human readable. However, in the end .sql wins this battle as a definite contender in braindead ways to verision your DB and the great thing is it is still contained within GitHub no other platforms are needed so we are using githubs powerful diffs... next up are the final comabtants. Thoguh they deliver on their promises they require an expert to wield them.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nFrom the dead Klonio, to these two compeeting (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/37385823/liquibase-vs-flyway-which-one-to-use) db migration tools: flyway(https://flywaydb.org/getstarted/download) and Liquibase(http://download.liquibase.org/) comes a start to what could become the github od db/\'s\r\n\r\nBoth use the command line and look like they require a certain degree of SQL knowledge, or other more involved knowledge sets to operate with any sort of confidence.','CMS WordPress DB Versioning and Syncing With GitHub: A \'how to\' on Continuous Deployment','','publish','open','closed','','cms-wordpress-db-versioning-and-syncing-with-github-a-how-to-on-continuous-deployment','','','2017-08-08 06:46:15','2017-08-08 06:46:15','',0,'http://www.localhost/fco/?p=498',0,'post','',0),(499,1,'2017-08-05 15:37:14','2017-08-05 15:37:14','','post-db-sync-versioning-continuos deploymnet-git','','inherit','open','closed','','post-db-sync-versioning-continuos-deploymnet-git','','','2017-08-05 15:37:14','2017-08-05 15:37:14','',498,'http://www.localhost/fco/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/post-db-sync-versioning-continuos-deploymnet-git.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(500,1,'2017-08-05 15:37:21','2017-08-05 15:37:21','Not well  documented but I think i have figured it out.... Only stack exchange offered manual answers, and there was a wp plugin. All other solutions are expensive as hell.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nobviously in 2010 it was still an issue\r\n\r\nfound this round about way on the way bottom of the discussion\r\n\r\nhttps://stackoverflow.com/questio